<div class="header">Description</div>
{{Quote|I know how tempting it is to go here, especially considering the low risk class and the "new color", but it's really not worth it.|color=#30BFBF}}
{{Blurimage|file=Olohood.png|caption=A picture of '''Level 912''''s exterior. Note how the colors are significantly dimmed down in photographs.|hovertext=Big mistake.}}
Level 912, nicknamed "Livin' in <span style="color:#64ffda;">Olo</span>" under popular decision by its entities, is an unusually desolate American suburb. The level contains [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ranch-style_house ranch-style] architecture and furnishing styled after "American Dream" ideals. These styles emerged shortly after WWII and were prevalent in the 1950s and 60s, albeit the fact that this level has the presence of modern vehicles and technology.

Only a few buildings are present throughout the interconnected cul-de-sacs, with everything in the interior and exterior painted in a unique turquoise paint, described by wanderers as "unlike any color", being much more saturated than regular shades of turquoise.


<div class="header">Discovery</div>
{{Blurimage|file=Olointerior.jpg|caption=An interior bathroom of one of the few houses.}}
The previously unidentified level, according to multiple accounts, was first experienced in 1952 by several wanderers, claiming that they had entered a level not unlike their previous homes in the [[The Frontrooms|Frontrooms]]. The affected wanderers had reportedly been acting giddy and ecstatic about the prospect of a level with indescribable beauty, matching their visions of the United States of America's future. Almost all of the wanderers had subsequently developed depression due to other levels [[Phenomenon 25|never being able to meet their expectations]].

These early claims were initially dismissed by the [[M.E.G.]] due to the inability to discover the level, and due to the "dreamlike quality" being attributed to either bad memory or [[Level 78|lucid dreams]]. However, starting April 2025, wanderers spontaneously started remembering a level they claimed to be a half-empty suburban neighborhood, painted almost entirely in turquoise. An entrance to the level was discovered in [[Level 85]] shortly after, confirming the level's existence.


<div class="header">Entities</div>
{{Blurimage|file=Oloman.png|caption=A male Proud American Patriot in his 30s.}}
The level is currently known to house only one type of entity, dozens of "<span style="color:#64ffda;">olo</span>-colored" humanoid figures that appear to be an odd subspecies (Homo corruptum <span style="color:#64ffda;">olo</span>) of [[Entity 9|Facelings]], who call their species "Proud American Patriots" (henceforth referred to as PAPs) upon being questioned on what they are. Several vintage photos of these so-called PAPs constructing the houses of Level 912 are present throughout.

It is strongly believed that the PAPs adopted "<span style="color:#64ffda;">olo</span> paints" (as seen on the labels of various paint buckets near houses) soon after Californian scientists from the Frontrooms had published their discovery on a "new color", caused by firing lasers into people's eyes which stimulated the retina to view an intense blue-green color that was soon dubbed "<span style="color:#64ffda;">olo</span>" by the scientists.

PAPs are generally not highly careful of their environment, often littering and tossing newspapers on the street (it is to be noted that these newspapers regularly contain [[The Frontrooms|Frontrooms]] news subjects, another potential factor to their discovery of the "<span style="color:#64ffda;">olo</span>" color, which we can mutually comprehend the thought of) and acting ignorant of their surroundings and the emotions of non-PAPs, prioritizing those familiar to them and their country above everything else.

PAPs are also often nonchalant and oblivious to any topics that do not have to do with past events of the U.S.A. or its present state, oftentimes even going as far as to completely ignore any phrase that would imply superiority over the U.S. PAPs are generally respectful, albeit a bit harsh, to one-another. The PAPs often get together when marching in crowds and attending parades which occur on nearly every afternoon with clear weathers.

